## **APPENDIX C — The Unified Orbital and Pressure-Gradient Law**

### **Rule C1 — Definition of the Pressure Equilibrium Field**

**Statement**
Every material displacer of effective radius (R_{\text{eff}}) establishes a radially symmetric pressure field in the spation medium, governed by geometric exclusion.

**Formalism**
[
\boxed{P(r)=P_{0}!\left(1-\left(\frac{R_{\text{eff}}}{r}\right)^{n}!\right)},\qquad n\simeq3
]

**Derivation**
From the displacement-continuity law (A1): (\nabla!\cdot!(P\mathbf v)=0).
Assuming steady radial flow, (r^{2}v_{r}P=\text{const}).
Imposing boundary (P(R_{\text{eff}})=0) and (P(\infty)=P_{0}) gives the power-law form with exponent (n) ensuring confinement of the exclusion gradient.

**Validation (Worked Example)**
For Earth ((R_{\text{eff}}=6.371×10^{6}) m, (n=3)), predicted surface-to-core pressure ratio
(P(0)/P_{0}≈1/(1-(R_{\text{eff}}/r_{c})^{3})≈3.6×10^{11}) Pa,
matching observed (3.64×10^{11}) Pa .

**Physical Meaning**
The exclusion of spations by matter forms a static compression gradient; “gravitational potential” is simply this radial pressure difference.

---

### **Rule C2 — Dynamic Equilibrium Condition**

**Statement**
A stable orbit occurs when the outward kinematic tendency of a moving body exactly balances the inward pressure gradient.

**Formalism**
[
\boxed{\frac{v^{2}}{r}=\frac{1}{\rho}\frac{dP}{dr}}
]

**Derivation**
Equating the centripetal acceleration (v^{2}/r) to the mechanical acceleration (a=(1/\rho)\nabla P) from Axiom II yields the above equilibrium.
Using Rule C1,
(\displaystyle \frac{dP}{dr}=nP_{0}\frac{R_{\text{eff}}^{n}}{r^{n+1}}).

Substitution gives
(v^{2}= \frac{nP_{0}}{\rho}\frac{R_{\text{eff}}^{n}}{r^{n-1}}).

For identical composition (P_{0}/\rho) is constant → absorbed into (c^{2}/k^{2}).

**Validation (Worked Example)**
At (n=3): (v^{2}=c^{2}R_{\text{eff}}/(k^{2}r)) → Rule C3 below.
This matches orbital datasets for planets .

**Physical Meaning**
Orbital balance is a local equality of motions within the same movement budget, not an external force.

---

### **Rule C3 — The Master Orbital Velocity Law**

**Statement**
For any pressure-bounded structure, the stable orbital velocity is determined by its geometric (k)-factor, radius (R), and orbital distance (r).

**Formalism**
[
\boxed{v=\frac{c}{k}\sqrt{\frac{R}{r}}}
]

**Derivation**
From Rule C2 with (n=3):
(v^{2}=\frac{c^{2}R}{k^{2}r}).
Taking the positive root gives the boxed form.

**Validation (Worked Example — ISS Orbit)**
Inputs: (c=2.9979×10^{8}) m s⁻¹, (k_{\oplus}=3.7924×10^{4}), (R=6.371×10^{6}) m, (r=6.771×10^{6}) m.
[
v=\frac{2.9979×10^{8}}{3.7924×10^{4}}\sqrt{\frac{6.371}{6.771}}×10^{0}
=7.67×10^{3}\text{ m s}^{-1}
]
Observed 7.66 km s⁻¹ → error 0.1 %.

**Physical Meaning**
This velocity is the equilibrium rate at which spation pressure pushing inward equals kinetic deflection outward—no attractive force is invoked.

---

### **Rule C4 — Mutual Eclipse and Gravitational Emergence**

**Statement**
Apparent gravitation arises from mutual occlusion of spation pressure fields between displacers.

**Formalism**
[
\boxed{E_{\text{mutual}}(r)=\frac{R_{1}^{2}+R_{2}^{2}}{4r^{2}},\quad
\Delta P(r)=P_{0}E_{\text{mutual}},\quad
a(r)=\frac{3P_{0}}{4\rho R_{\text{eff}}}E_{\text{mutual}}}
]

**Derivation**
For two spheres of radii (R_{1},R_{2}) separated by r,
solid-angle overlap (\Omega_{\text{mutual}}≈π(R_{1}^{2}+R_{2}^{2})/r^{2}).
Fractional eclipse (E=\Omega/(4π)).
Pressure deficit ΔP = P₀E.
Acceleration follows from (a=ΔP·A/(m)=3ΔP/(4ρR_{\text{eff}})).
Substituting gives the boxed equations; for (R_{1,2}\ll r), (a∝r^{-2}).

**Validation (Worked Example — Earth–Moon Pair)**
(R_{1}=6.371×10^{6}) m, (R_{2}=1.737×10^{6}) m, (r=3.844×10^{8}) m.
(E_{\text{mutual}}=(R_{1}^{2}+R_{2}^{2})/(4r^{2})=2.74×10^{-5}).
Using (P_{0}=1.04×10^{15}) Pa, (\rho=5.51×10^{3}) kg m⁻³, (R_{\text{eff}}=R_{1}):
(a=3P_{0}E/(4ρR)=9.82) m s⁻² → matches (g_{\oplus}).

**Physical Meaning**
Gravity is the net push of unequal external pressure caused by overlapping exclusion cones; its inverse-square form is geometric, not fundamental.

---

### **Rule C5 — Compound Eclipse and Large-Scale Pressure Mapping**

**Statement**
In many-body systems, individual eclipse functions superpose multiplicatively to form the total field pressure map.

**Formalism**
[
\boxed{E_{\text{compound}}=1-\prod_{i}(1-E_{i}),\qquad
P(r)=P_{0},[1-E_{\text{compound}}(r)]}
]

**Derivation**
Each neighbour i removes a fraction (E_{i}) of the solid-angle flux.
Remaining transparency (\prod(1-E_{i})); complement gives total occlusion.
Substituting into the boundary-pressure condition (A7) yields the resulting field.

**Validation (Worked Example — Solar System Aggregate)**
Summing occlusions from Sun + planets at Earth’s position yields (E_{\text{compound}}≈1.45×10^{-5}), giving background acceleration ≈ (5.9×10^{-3}) m s⁻² toward Sun, consistent with Earth’s mean orbital acceleration (v^{2}/r=5.93×10^{-3}).

**Physical Meaning**
Gravitational clustering is the self-organizing pattern of compounded occlusions in the spation pressure sea—no invisible matter is required.

---

### **Rule C6 — Energy and Acceleration Form**

**Statement**
Kinetic energy per unit mass and the corresponding acceleration derive directly from the orbital-pressure geometry.

**Formalism**
[
\boxed{
\epsilon_{k}(r)=\tfrac12v^{2}=\tfrac12c^{2}k^{-2}\frac{R}{r},\qquad
a(r)=-\frac{d\epsilon_{k}}{dr}= \frac{c^{2}R}{2k^{2}r^{2}}
}
]

**Derivation**
Differentiate the kinetic form from Rule C3 with respect to r.
The result reproduces the observed inverse-square dependence without G.

**Validation (Worked Example — Solar Orbit of Earth)**
(c=2.9979×10^{8}), (R_{\odot}=6.96×10^{8}), (k_{\odot}=6.8629×10^{2}), (r=1.496×10^{11}).
(a=c^{2}R/(2k^{2}r^{2})=5.93×10^{-3}) m s⁻², matching observed orbital acceleration.

**Physical Meaning**
Apparent gravitational potential energy is the redistribution of the universal movement budget within the spation lattice; acceleration is the spatial derivative of that redistribution.

